@endnode

@node INSTALL "SSPro - 2.2 Installation of SSPro"
@toc TABLE

@{b}Installing SSProDemo:@{ub}

     1) Copy SSProDemo/libs/iff.library to your libs: directory

     2) Copy SSProDemo/fonts/#? to your fonts: directory

     3) Copy the SSProDemo directory to wherever you want it.


@{b}Installing the registered version on a hard drive:@{ub}

     1) Boot your computer the way you normally would

     2) Insert the SSPro_Install disk

     3) Open the SSPro_Install disk icon

     4) Double-Click on the Install-SSPro icon

     5) Follow the Installer instructions


@{b}Running the registered version from floppy:@{ub}

     You can run SSPro from floppies, but obviously, the system will be
limited.  Just boot as you normally would, copy the file Utils/iff.library to
your libs: directory, open the SSPro_Install disk and run directly from it.
It's that simple.  Note that the sample depth images and brush patterns are
compressed, and you will need to decompress them if you wish to use them.


@{b}Testing the System:@{ub}

     To make sure that everything is installed correctly, try double-clicking
on the SSPro icon!  If the SSPro window comes up, with no errors, then all
files were installed correctly.  If it does not come up, or there are any
errors, check to see if the iff.library is located in your LIBS: directory, and
try running SSPro again.


@endnode

@node WORK "SSPro - 3.1 How Stereograms Work"
@toc TABLE

     Look closely at a stereogram.  Don't look at it Wall-Eyed, just look at
the monitor surface.  If you notice, there is a repeating pattern horizontally.
What happens, is when you focus beyond the screen (Wall-Eyed), your left eye is
looking at one image, and the right eye is looking at the image on the right.
Your mind takes those two different images and creates a 3D image.  The
following examples explain this further.


          @{b}Normal viewing of image@{ub}
          (You see one, 2D image)

     ---------------*-----------------  <-- Image surface
                   / \\
                  /   \\  <-- Lines of Sight from each eye
                 /     \\
                /       \\
              (*)       (*)  <-- Your eyes



        @{b}Wall-Eyed viewing of image@{ub}
           (You see a 3D image)

                    *   <-- Perceived image depth (in 3D)
                   / \\
     -------------*---*---------------  <-- Image surface
                 /     \\
                /       \\  <-- Lines of sight from each eye
               /         \\
              (*)       (*)  <-- Your eyes


     Because your left eye sees one "*" and the right eye sees the other "*",
the two combine in your mind and you think that you are looking at an "*" that
is deeper than the surface of the image and in 3D.

     By adjusting the distance between the repeating pattern, your mind
interprets it as varying depths. So:


     --------------**----------------  <-- Image surface


     -------------*--*---------------  <-- Image surface (looks deeper)


     ------------*----*--------------  <-- Image surface (looks deeper yet)


@endnode

@node STEREO "SSPro - 3.2 How SSPro Generates Stereograms"
@toc TABLE

     First, start off with a repeating brush pattern for your background, this
defines the maximum depth of your image:

@{b} 1@{ub}   ASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKL
@{b} 2@{ub}   ASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKL
@{b} 3@{ub}   ASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKL
@{b} 4@{ub}   ASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKL
@{b} 5@{ub}   ASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKL
@{b} 6@{ub}   ASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKL
@{b} 7@{ub}   ASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKL
@{b} 8@{ub}   ASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKL

     You should be able to look at the previous block of characters Wall-Eyed
and see that it looks deeper than the surface.  Notice that the edges are
blurry.  All stereograms are blurry on the edges, this is because when you get
way to one side, only one eye can see the brush pattern, and you loose the 3D
effect.  In the previous block, notice that the repeat brush pattern is
"ASDFGHJKL" or 9 characters.  By removing all the "H" from rows 2-7 in repeat
columns 2-7, then filling in the same repeat on the right, you get the
following:

@{b}     |   1    |   2    |   3    |   4    |   5    |   6    |   7    |   8@{ub}

@{b} 1@{ub}   ASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKL
@{b} 2@{ub}   ASDFGHJKLASDFGJKLASDFGJKLASDFGJKLASDFGJKLASDFGJKLASDFGJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGH
@{b} 3@{ub}   ASDFGHJKLASDFGJKLASDFGJKLASDFGJKLASDFGJKLASDFGJKLASDFGJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGH
@{b} 4@{ub}   ASDFGHJKLASDFGJKLASDFGJKLASDFGJKLASDFGJKLASDFGJKLASDFGJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGH
@{b} 5@{ub}   ASDFGHJKLASDFGJKLASDFGJKLASDFGJKLASDFGJKLASDFGJKLASDFGJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGH
@{b} 6@{ub}   ASDFGHJKLASDFGJKLASDFGJKLASDFGJKLASDFGJKLASDFGJKLASDFGJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGH
@{b} 7@{ub}   ASDFGHJKLASDFGJKLASDFGJKLASDFGJKLASDFGJKLASDFGJKLASDFGJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGH
@{b} 8@{ub}   ASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKL

     Notice how it stands out in the middle?  Now I'll add another level to the
image.  Notice that when the image moves back down, the repeat pattern gets
messed up and other characters are introduced:


@{b}     |   1    |   2    |   3    |   4    |   5    |   6    |   7    |   8@{ub}

@{b} 1@{ub}   ASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKL
@{b} 2@{ub}   ASDFGHJKLASDFGJKLASDFGJKLASDFGJKLASDFGJKLASDFGJKLASDFGJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGH
@{b} 3@{ub}   ASDFGHJKLASDFGJKLASDFJKLASDFJKLASDFJKLASDFJKLASDFJKLASDFXJKLASYDFXJKLASY
@{b} 4@{ub}   ASDFGHJKLASDFGJKLASDFJKLASDFJKLASDFJKLASDFJKLASDFJKLASDFXJKLASYDFXJKLASY
@{b} 5@{ub}   ASDFGHJKLASDFGJKLASDFJKLASDFJKLASDFJKLASDFJKLASDFJKLASDFXJKLASYDFXJKLASY
@{b} 6@{ub}   ASDFGHJKLASDFGJKLASDFJKLASDFJKLASDFJKLASDFJKLASDFJKLASDFXJKLASYDFXJKLASY
@{b} 7@{ub}   ASDFGHJKLASDFGJKLASDFGJKLASDFGJKLASDFGJKLASDFGJKLASDFGJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGH
@{b} 8@{ub}   ASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKLASDFGHJKL

     Notice that the last repeat brush pattern on rows 3-6, column 8 are now
"DFXJKLASY", not "ASDFGHJKL".  This is the same reason that graphic stereograms
sometimes seem smeared to one side, the other, or both.


@endnode

@node INTERFACE "SSPro - 4.1 Using the Interface"
@toc TABLE

     The interface is really quite simple, and you should have no problem if
you are familiar with other Amiga interfaces.  All functions can either be
selected via window gadgets, pull-down menus or the CLI.


  @{b}Window Gadgets@{ub}            @{b}Pull-Down Menus@{ub}           @{b}CLI Interface@{ub}
  @{"  Project     " link WPROJECT}           @{"  Project      " link MPROJECT}           @{"  Interface  " link CLI}
  @{"  Options     " link WOPTIONS}           @{"  Options      " link MOPTIONS}
  @{"  Techniques  " link TECHNIQUES}           @{"  Render       " link RENDER}
  @{"  Switches    " link SWITCHES}           @{"  Image        " link IMAGE}
  @{"  Render      " link RENDER}
  @{"  Image       " link IMAGE}


@endnode

@node WPROJECT "SSPro - 4.1.1 Using the Interface - Project"
@toc TABLE

@{b}(Open) Brush Pattern@{ub}
     This is where you select the brush image that will be used as the
     background pattern for your stereogram.

@{b}(Open) Depth Image@{ub}
     This allows you to select an image that will be used as the 3D source for
     your stereogram.  This image is typically a grey-scale.

@{b}Save Image As@{ub}
     Use this to decide where to save the created stereogram.  When rendering is
     complete, SSPro will automatically save the stereogram as the filename
     selected here.


@endnode

@node WOPTIONS "SSPro - 4.1.2 Using the Interface - Options"
@toc TABLE

@{b}Output (Resolution)@{ub}
     Allows you to set the output image size.  You can type in any resolution
     up to and including 9000x32000, or select one of the default or custom
     resolutions from the menu.

     @{b}Define@{ub} @{i}(only on the menu)@{ui}
          To change the custom resolutions, select Define from the Output
          Resolution menu.  You will be prompted with a listing of the current
          custom resolutions defined.  Just change any settings desired and
          close the window.  The menu will now reflect these changes.
          Remember, to save these changes, you must select Save Default Config
          from the Project menu!

@{b}Auto Adjustment / Eye Width / % Depth@{ub} @{i}(Eye Width & % Depth are only gadgets)@{ui}
     Eye Width and % Depth allow you to set the background depth and depth
     image depth in 3D space.  For starters, it is easier to just click on the
     "Normal" gadget and SSPro will pick a screen viewable width and depth for
     you.  If you are going to print the created stereogram, click on the
     "300dpi" gadget and SSPro will pick a viewable width and depth for you.
     For more information on Eye Width and % Depth, refer to the section
     @{"Width & % Depth" link WIDTHDEPTH}.

@{b}Darkness@{ub} @{i}(only a windows gadget)@{ui}
     Determines the amount of black in a SIRDS render. A Darkness value of 0
     would give a mostly black SIRDS, while 50 would render very little black.
     Setting Darkness to 25, the default, results in an even division of all
     colors in the SIRDS.  Note that this is only active if you are rendering
     with a SIRDS technique.

@{b}Seed@{ub} @{i}(only a windows gadget)@{ui}
     Allows you to set the random seed, 0=random, anything else will fix on
     that seed.


@endnode

@node TECHNIQUES "SSPro - 4.1.3 Using the Interface - Techniques"
@toc TABLE

     In SSPro, the Techniques are broken-up into several different options.
This is done to give you as MANY different rendering combinations as possible.
Because many different effects are desired, and tastes vary from person to
person, over 100 Techniques are possible.  Following is an explanation the
these Techniques.

@{b}Render Method@{ub}
  (1) @{i}SIRDS (default) @{ui}-Single Image Random Dot Stereograms.  Automatically
    generates the random dot pattern for you.
  (2) Brush Pattern - System loads the brush specified in the Brush Pattern
    field.

@{b}SIRDS Colors@{ub} @{i}(only available in SIRDS Render Method)@{ui}
  (1) @{i}2 Color (default) @{ui}
  (2) 4 Color
  (3) 8 Color
  (4) 16 Color

@{b}Linear Direction@{ub}
  (1) Left-Right - Renders from the left side of the image to the right.
  (2) Right-Left - Renders from the right side of the image to the left.
  (3) @{i}Symmetric (default) @{ui}- Renders from the middle out, this reduces tearing.
  (4) Smart Direction - Automatically picks best direction for each line.

@{b}Render Technique@{ub}
  (1) Random Color - Best used for true random dot brush patterns.  With this,
    you could create your own random dot brush pattern with your own palette.
    If using a Brush Pattern, a lot of graininess is added to the image.
  (2) Nearby Color - Best used for Brush Patterns that have different colors in
    each row.  It will pick a random color from the current row, therefore, it
    will not introduce additional colors.  This Technique will not be as grainy
    as the Random Color is.
  (3) Smart Block - Best used for Brush Patterns.  It looks at the depth
    changes and besides the best color block to capture.  This Technique will
    not be grainy as in Random or Nearby Color.
  (4) Last Block - Best used for Brush Patterns.  This is very similar to Smart
    Block, except that it always uses the last block.  Sometimes, this
    Technique looks slightly better than Smart Block, other times it looks
    worse.  It all depends on the image being rendered and the Brush Pattern.
  (5) @{i}Dithered Block (default) @{ui}- Best used for Brush Patterns.  This is very
    similar to Smart Block, except that it doesn't allow a quick transition
    from close to far away pixels.  This makes it a very good general purpose
    Technique.  However, sometimes it gives a mechanical look, if it does, use
    Smart Block or Last Block.
  (6) Smeared Block - Best used for Brush Patterns.  With this technique, it
    takes the last color and simply smears it.  This is a very popular
    stereogram technique.  However, it does not give results as good as Smart,
    Last, or Dithered Block.  It is best used for Depth Images that have
    gradual transitions, or if you use smaller % Depth values.

@{b}Brush Height Adjustment@{ub} @{i}(only available with Render Method of Brush Pattern)@{ui}
  (1) Keep Height - Don't adjust the brush height.
  (2) Stretch Height - Stretch the brush height to match the Output Resolution
    height.
  (3) @{i}Keep Aspect (default) @{ui}- Keep the brush aspect ratio 1:1 (width:height)


@endnode

@node SWITCHES "SSPro - 4.1.4 Using the Interface - Switches"
@toc TABLE

@{b}Color Sort@{ub}
     Sorts 32, 16, 8, 4, or 2 color depth images in order of intensity.  So,
     brightest is in front, while darkest is in the background.
     @{i}Note: Does nothing if using an 8 or 24-bit Depth Image.@{ui}

@{b}Cross-Eyed@{ub}
     Inverts the rendering so you can use the Cross-Eyed method of viewing
     instead of Wall-Eyed.
     @{i}Note: Sometimes stereograms will not look correct with this mode.@{ui}

@{b}Show-Eyes@{ub}
     Renders two "eyes" at the top of the image to help in viewing the
     stereogram.

@{b}Smoothing@{ub}
     Renders depth using the Burkes dithering method, thus smoothing the
     stair-step effects.
     @{i}Note: Disabled if Cross-Eyed switch is selected.@{ui}

@{b}Granular@{ub}
     Will only render every other row, which speeds up rendering by about 2
     times.  This looses quality, but is a great time saver for testing.
     @{i}Note: Disabled if rendering in Virtual Memory Mode.@{ui}

@{b}Beep Cancel@{ub}
     Will cancel the system beep that occurs after rendering is complete.


@endnode

@node RENDER "SSPro - 4.1.5 Using the Interface - Render"
@toc TABLE

@{b}Quick Render@{ub}
     This allows you to quickly get a good idea on how your rendered image will
     look.  It will render a 320x200 (320x256 PAL) image using your current
     settings.  If the aspect ratio of the output resolution is not standard,
     it will use a resolution to match as close as possible.  After quick
     rendering is done, click the left mouse button to continue.

@{b}Render@{ub}
     Use this to render just one image.  This will render your current settings
     and save the image as the specified filename.  During rendering, if you
     are not in Virtual Memory Mode, or rendering a non-viewable screen, you
     can click the "Display Image" gadget to view the stereogram as it is being
     created.  Clicking on the stereogram will return you to the SSPro
     interface.  Clicking the "Abort Rendering" gadget on the status window
     will also give obvious results.

@{b}Select@{ub}
     Use this when you wish to render multiple images.  You can keep changing
     your options, filenames, etc. and each time, selecting "Select".  When you
     are done selecting and you wish to render the images(s) selected, click on
     the "Render All" gadget.  SSPro will render all images selected.

@{b}Render All@{ub}
     See "Select" above.


@endnode

@node IMAGE "SSPro - 4.1.6 Using the Interface - Image"
@toc TABLE

@{b}View (Image)@{ub}
     Use this to display any IFF image types except HAM or HAM8.  While viewing
     you can move your mouse to scroll around the image or hit the left mouse
     button to cancel.
     @{i}Note: 256 color images are converted to 16 colors with no dithering.
           24-bit images are converted to 16 color gray scale images.
           This is done to speed up viewing time.  Images remain as 256 color
           and 24-bit.@{ui}

@{b}Print (Image)@{ub}
     This will print an IFF using the PrinterGfx Preferences settings.  In
     Preferences, setting the Dithering to Halftone, Aspect to Vertical, Type
     to Absolute, Width to 10.5, and Height to 8.0, will give you very nice
     results.  Note that at the present time, SSPro will not print a 256 color
     or 24-bit image.

@{b}Delete (Image)@{ub}
     Obviously, this will delete an image.


@endnode

@node MPROJECT "SSPro - 4.1.7 Using the Interface - Project"
@toc TABLE

@{b}Open Brush Pattern...@{ub} @{" Description " link WPROJECT}

@{b}Open Depth Image...@{ub}   @{" Description " link WPROJECT}

@{b}Save Image As...@{ub}      @{" Description " link WPROJECT}

~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
@{b}Open Config...@{ub}
     Allows you to open a custom configuration file.

@{b}Save Config As...@{ub}
     Allows you to save the current settings as a custom configuration file.

@{b}Save Default Config@{ub}
     Save current settings as the default configuration.

~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
@{b}About...@{ub}
     View information on program version and how to reach the author.

~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
@{b}Quit@{ub}
     Obviously quits SSPro.


@endnode

@node MOPTIONS "SSPro - 4.1.8 Using the Interface - Options"
@toc TABLE

@{b}Output Resolution@{ub} @{" Description " link WOPTIONS}

~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
@{b}Auto Adjust@{ub}       @{" Description " link WOPTIONS}

~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

@{b}Render Method@{ub}     @{" Description " link TECHNIQUES}

@{b}SIRDS Colors@{ub}      @{" Description " link TECHNIQUES}

@{b}Linear Direction@{ub}  @{" Description " link TECHNIQUES}

@{b}Render Technique@{ub}  @{" Description " link TECHNIQUES}

@{b}Brush Height Adj.@{ub} @{" Description " link TECHNIQUES}

~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
